Leviathan is a great beginner-friendly wargame from OverTheWire that introduces local enumeration, binary exploitation, and basic privilege escalation — all in a safe CTF-style lab.

![][image2]

But strings doesn’t tell us **how the program checks** the password. So we move to:

Press enter or click to view image in full size

![][image10]

***ltrace ./check***

Why ltrace?

* It shows **dynamic function calls** from shared libraries like strcmp(), printf(), getchar(), etc.  
* It’s perfect for spotting **what your input is compared to** inside a binary.

It prompts for a password: I try pass but it shows wrong password but then I notice what’s written in the message “strcmp”

The binary is comparing your input pas to the hardcoded string "sex"

now running it again and entering the password correctly while running it:

Press enter or click to view image in full size

![][image11]

***./check***

***password: sex***

it gives you shell access and we know that because we see this also: system(“/bin/sh”)

***cd /etc/leviathan\_pass***  
***ls \-la***

we see: leviathan2

***cat leviathan2***

***![][image12]***

and BOOM\! we get the password
